                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d323">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9102: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-31T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 31, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 31—6:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>346. Department’s 115, July 13, 2 p.m.<note n="29" xml:id="d323fn29">Not
                        printed.</note> and my 247, July 16, 6 p.m. from Peiping. In a conversation
                    which I had with British and French Ambassadors yesterday it appeared that
                    communication made to French Foreign Office by Japanese Ambassador in Paris was
                    not made to British Foreign Office by Japanese Ambassador there. Can Department
                    inform me whether Japanese Ambassador in Washington gave any assurances
                    regarding South China or made any statement as to Japanese intentions in regard
                    to North China?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
